    "Name": "latency_aware_layer_skipping_jacobian_pac_bayes",
    "Title": "Latency-Aware Layer-Skipping Inference Using Jacobian-Based PAC-Bayes Frameworks",
    "Short Hypothesis": "By leveraging Jacobian-based analysis and PAC-Bayes frameworks, we can develop a latency-aware layer-skipping inference mechanism that minimizes hidden-state perturbation while strictly enforcing wall-clock budgets.",
    "Related Work": "Existing works like SNIP and AMP-ViT focus on adaptive precision and mixed-precision quantization but do not address layer-skipping inference. HiLoRA explores adaptive hierarchical LoRA routing but does not incorporate Jacobian-based analysis or PAC-Bayes frameworks. This proposal uniquely combines these elements to address latency-aware inference.",
    "Abstract": "This paper proposes a novel latency-aware layer-skipping inference mechanism using Jacobian-based analysis and PAC-Bayes frameworks. The approach minimizes hidden-state perturbation while strictly enforcing wall-clock budgets, ensuring efficient and accurate inference. We introduce a Jacobian-based layer-skipping framework that dynamically adjusts layer activation based on perturbation-cost metrics derived from PAC-Bayes stability bounds. Experiments on standard benchmarks demonstrate significant improvements in throughput-accuracy Pareto frontiers, with explicit perturbation-cost and memory-bandwidth accounting. The proposed method offers a compute-frugal solution for latency-critical applications, bridging the gap between theoretical guarantees and practical deployment.",
    "Experiments": [
