{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "curvature_aware_mixed_precision",
    "Title": "Curvature-Aware Mixed Precision Quantization via Deterministic Subspace Routing",
    "Short Hypothesis": "By explicitly coupling Hessian curvature diagnostics with deterministic subspace routing, we can achieve training-free mixed-precision quantization with formal stability guarantees and minimal computational overhead.",
    "Related Work": "Existing mixed-precision quantization methods either rely on heuristic proxies (EMQ, AMP-ViT) or require costly quantization-aware training (SNIP). While some recent works explore curvature-based approaches (ILD-MPQ, GAMMA), they lack formal stability analysis and deterministic execution guarantees. Our proposal uniquely integrates Hessian subspace diagnostics with a deterministic routing protocol, providing explicit condition number constraints and numerical stability radii.",
    "Abstract": "Mixed-precision quantization offers a promising approach to optimize the accuracy-efficiency trade-off in deep neural networks. However, existing methods often rely on heuristic proxies or costly training procedures, lacking formal stability guarantees. We propose a novel framework that couples Hessian curvature diagnostics with deterministic subspace routing to achieve training-free mixed-precision quantization. Our approach introduces a curvature-aware precision routing protocol that explicitly quantifies gradient covariance decay and Hessian conditioning, enabling formal stability analysis through PAC-Bayes generalization bounds and condition number constraints. We enforce deterministic execution pathways by adopting coarse-grained, block-level precision tiering, which guarantees strict computational overhead bounds while preserving architectural coherence. Extensive experiments on vision transformers and large language models demonstrate that our method achieves state-of-the-art accuracy-efficiency trade-offs, with formal stability guarantees and minimal computational overhead.",
    "Experiments": [
      "Conduct Hessian subspace diagnostics to quantify curvature properties across different layers and blocks in vision transformers (ViT, DeiT) and large language models (LLaMA, GPT).",
      "Implement deterministic subspace routing protocol based on curvature diagnostics, assigning precision tiers to different blocks while maintaining formal stability constraints.",
      "Evaluate the proposed method on ImageNet and GLUE benchmarks, comparing against state-of-the-art mixed-precision quantization methods (EMQ, AMP-ViT, SNIP).",
      "Perform formal stability analysis using PAC-Bayes generalization bounds and condition number constraints, quantifying the robustness of our method to numerical perturbations.",
      "Measure computational overhead and inference latency on single-GPU setups, ensuring strict bounds on resource utilization."
    ],
    "Risk Factors and Limitations": [
      "The effectiveness of Hessian subspace diagnostics may vary across different architectures and tasks, potentially limiting the generalizability of the approach.",
      "The deterministic routing protocol may introduce additional computational overhead during the initial diagnostic phase, although this is amortized over subsequent inference runs.",
      "The coarse-grained, block-level precision tiering may not fully capture fine-grained precision requirements in certain layers, potentially leaving some efficiency gains untapped.",
      "The formal stability analysis relies on theoretical bounds that may be conservative in practice, potentially underestimating the actual robustness of the method."
    ]
  }
}
```

This proposal distinguishes from existing work by explicitly coupling Hessian curvature diagnostics with deterministic subspace routing, providing formal stability guarantees and deterministic execution pathways. It addresses the limitations of heuristic proxies and costly training procedures in current mixed-precision quantization methods, while maintaining strict computational overhead bounds and architectural coherence.
